=========================================
std::shared_ptr (C++11)
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================
1. What is std::shared_ptr?
---------------------------
std::shared_ptr is a C++11 smart pointer that allows
multiple smart pointers to share ownership of the same object.
The object is automatically destroyed when the last owner releases it.
Header
#include <memory>
-----------------------------------------

2. Why shared_ptr?
------------------
Use unique_ptr when there is only one owner.
Use shared_ptr when multiple objects need to own the same resource.

Example
Employee object used by multiple departments.

        Employee
        /   |   \
      HR   IT  Payroll

All three departments use the same Employee object.
-----------------------------------------

3. Simple Example
-----------------

auto emp = make_shared<Employee>();

shared_ptr<Employee> hr = emp;
shared_ptr<Employee> it = emp;
shared_ptr<Employee> payroll = emp;

All point to the SAME object.
Reference Count = 4

emp
hr
it
payroll

When the last shared_ptr is destroyed,
Employee is automatically deleted.

-----------------------------------------

4. Reference Counting
---------------------

Every copy increases the reference count.

shared_ptr<int> p1 = make_shared<int>(10);

Reference Count = 1

shared_ptr<int> p2 = p1;

Reference Count = 2

shared_ptr<int> p3 = p2;

Reference Count = 3

When one owner goes away

p2.reset();

Reference Count = 2

When count becomes zero

Object is deleted automatically.

-----------------------------------------

5. Control Block
----------------

shared_ptr internally maintains a Control Block.

It stores

• Reference count
• Weak pointer count
• Custom deleter (if any)

Conceptually

shared_ptr ----\
                \
                 Control Block -----> Object
                /
shared_ptr ----/

-----------------------------------------

6. make_shared()
----------------

Preferred
auto p = make_shared<Employee>();

Avoid
shared_ptr<Employee> p(new Employee);

Why?
• Faster (single allocation)
• Exception safe
• Cleaner

