7. Common Member Functions
--------------------------

use_count()
Returns current reference count.
cout << p.use_count();

------------------------

get()
Returns raw pointer.
Employee* raw = p.get();
Ownership remains with shared_ptr.

------------------------

reset()
Releases ownership.

p.reset();
Reference count decreases.

If count becomes zero,
object is destroyed.

------------------------

operator*

Access object.

cout << *p;

------------------------

operator->

Access members.

p->display();

-----------------------------------------

8. Copy vs Move
---------------

Copy
shared_ptr<int> p2 = p1;

✔ Allowed
Reference count increases.

Move
shared_ptr<int> p2 = std::move(p1);

Ownership transferred.
Reference count unchanged.

p1 becomes nullptr.

-----------------------------------------

9. Thread Safety
----------------

Reference count updates are thread-safe.

Different threads can safely copy/destroy shared_ptr.

Accessing the managed object is NOT thread-safe.

Protect shared data using mutex if needed.

-----------------------------------------

10. Circular Reference Problem**********
------------------------------

class A
{
    shared_ptr<B> b;
};

class B
{
    shared_ptr<A> a;
};

A and B keep each other alive forever.

Reference count never becomes zero.

Memory leak occurs.

-----------------------------------------

11. Solution : weak_ptr
-----------------------

Replace one shared_ptr with weak_ptr.

class A
{
    shared_ptr<B> b;
};

class B
{
    weak_ptr<A> a;
};

Now

Reference count reaches zero.

Objects are destroyed correctly.

-----------------------------------------

12. shared_ptr vs unique_ptr
----------------------------

unique_ptr

• One owner
• No reference counting
• Faster
• Cannot copy
• Can move

shared_ptr

• Multiple owners
• Reference counting
• Slight overhead
• Copy allowed
• Move allowed

